      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation performed across three mesh densities (coarse 0.8 mm, medium 0.4 mm, fine 0.2 mm global seed). GCI values: stiffness 1.2%, yield force 1.8%, force at 40 mm 2.1%. All below 5% threshold. Fine mesh selected for production runs. Achieved level 3 due to additional p-refinement study confirming element-order independence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver convergence criteria documented; force and displacement residuals < 1e-4 for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear Newton-Raphson solver with force residual tolerance 1e-5 and displacement residual tolerance 1e-5. All 11 model runs converged without bisection beyond the first load step. Energy balance checked post-solution; artificial energy < 0.1% of total internal energy in all cases."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts by a qualified analyst not involved in model development.",
      "rationale": "Independent review conducted by a senior biomechanical engineer (10 years FEA experience) not involved in model construction. Review checklist covered geometry import, material assignment, contact definitions, boundary condition application, and QoI extraction scripts. Two minor discrepancies in contact pair ordering corrected prior to production runs; no material or BC errors found."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form uncertainty quantified and documented; physics assumptions (linear vs. nonlinear material, contact formulation) justified relative to the COU at required level 3.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening material model for Ti-6Al-4V validated against coupon tensile data (R²=0.997). Augmented Lagrangian contact formulation selected based on literature benchmarks for threaded fastener interfaces. Geometric nonlinearity enabled throughout. Model form uncertainty estimated at ±4% on stiffness QoI via comparison of three constitutive model variants; documented in VVP-MF-001. Screening sensitivity of elastic modulus (±5 GPa) showed < 1.5% change in all QoIs, confirming low model-form sensitivity to this parameter."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties and geometric inputs traceable to measured or certified sources; input uncertainty characterised at required level 3.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties sourced from certified material test reports for each production lot (E = 113.8 ± 1.2 GPa, σ_y = 880 ± 15 MPa). UHMWPE block properties from supplier data sheet with three-point confirmation tests. Screw geometry from CAD nominal with dimensional inspection report confirming < 0.05 mm deviation on critical features. Input uncertainty propagated via informal screening analysis documented in engineering notebook EN-2023-047; friction coefficient μ = 0.15 ± 0.05 yielded < 2.8% variation in stiffness QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples representative of production geometry and material; N ≥ 10 constructs with traceability to production lots at required level 3.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-representative screws (same lot as clinical supply) and UHMWPE blocks per ASTM F1717 specification. Six constructs tested at Laboratory 1 (FDA CDRH), five at Laboratory 2 (DePuy Synthes). Dimensional inspection of all screws prior to assembly; all within drawing tolerances. Material certs available for all hardware. Inter-laboratory variability < 4% on mean stiffness, confirming sample and protocol consistency."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of COU loading scenarios; multiple load levels or configurations tested at required level 3.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single loading configuration (compression-bending per ASTM F1717 at 5° angulation, 10 mm/min crosshead speed) as specified by the standard. Only one test condition evaluated; required level 3 demands multiple conditions (e.g., varying angulation or rate). Achieved level 2 because inter-laboratory replication confirms reproducibility but does not add configurational breadth. This shortfall is acknowledged; additional loading conditions are planned for a future validation study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters demonstrably equivalent to test conditions; any differences between model and test characterised and their effect on QoIs bounded at required level 3.",
      "rationale": "Model geometry matches test hardware to within dimensional inspection tolerances (< 0.05 mm). Applied displacement boundary condition replicates crosshead motion; load cell compliance not modelled but estimated < 0.3% effect on stiffness QoI. UHMWPE block material properties assigned from same lot as test specimens. Torque preload on screws replicated in model via pretension element with measured installation torque (4.0 ± 0.2 N·m). Equivalency documented in VVP-EIP-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E/uval) applied to all QoIs with pre-established acceptance bounds; comparison accounts for both model and experimental uncertainty at required level 3.",
      "rationale": "E/uval metric applied per ASME V&V 40 Section 8. Combined validation uncertainty uval computed from experimental repeatability (pooled standard deviation across both labs) and model numerical uncertainty (GCI + input uncertainty RSS combination). All three QoIs: E/uval ≤ 1.12, well below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences ≤ 3.1%, below the 10% pre-established bound. Comparison plots with uncertainty bands provided in VVP-OC-001. The informal screening sensitivity study (EN-2023-047) confirmed that input variability contributes < 3% to uval, supporting the robustness of the comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to the clinical risk and regulatory decision; justification documented at required level 3.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and directly linked to clinical performance (construct rigidity for fusion, resistance to permanent deformation under physiological loading). All three QoIs are used in the 510(k) substantial equivalence argument. Linkage to clinical risk documented in the risk analysis (RA-2023-012, FMEA line items 14–17)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
